From: John Nelson <JohnNelson@Cunet.Carleton.Ca>
Sent: Monday, January 13, 2025 4:28 AM
To: Joe(Beiqiao) Hu <BeiqiaoHu@cmail.carleton.ca>
Cc: Tony Bailetti <TonyBailetti@cunet.carleton.ca>; Dan Premachuk <DanPrema=
chuk@CUNET.CARLETON.CA>
Subject: RE: Request for Support: Perplexity Sharing Session at the Innovat=
ion Hub


Hello Joe,

 I need to have a quick chat about the Perplexity session that you had orig=
inally planned to have in the Innovation Hub on Tuesday January 20.   I ant=
icipated a few challenges as we got things set up given the university=92s =
approach to introducing new AI tools for widespread use on campus and as ex=
pected, the event (in its current form) has been flagged for two main reaso=
ns.



Challenges



  1.  First and foremost, Perplexity has not yet been through the universit=
y=92s security and privacy assessment process<https://carleton.ca/its/secur=
ity/services/risk-assessment/>.
     *   A Data Protection Risk Assessment (DPRA) is a process involving th=
e Service Delivery & Quality group, the Information Security group, and the=
 Privacy Office that is used to determine the level of risk to security and=
 privacy of data associated with the purchase and use of an IT system or se=
rvice. The outcome of a DPRA is a detailed report that lists the risks asso=
ciated with the IT system or service, a score identifying the risk level, a=
nd recommendation(s) to address any significant risks identified. With this=
 report, the client is able to make informed decisions about the purchase o=
f an IT system or service to protect the users of the system, and the unive=
rsity as a whole.
     *   Before the Hub can be involved in a session that actively promotes=
 the use of one specific tool over another, that tool needs to be taken thr=
ough the university=92s process.  As I mentioned before, Microsoft Copilot =
is the University=92s Recommended Generative AI Platform<https://carleton.c=
a/its/2024/copilot-university-recommended-generative-ai-platform/> so as we=
 continue to explore other options, we need to ensure that  the same level =
of due diligence is used.
  2.  Secondly, it is important that this session includes some references =
to the appropriate use of AI in academic work and the importance of accommo=
dating for academic integrity to be maintained. This continues to be an imp=
ortant topic on campus and a number of faculty members are working alongsid=
e students and staff to find appropriate ways to help students leverage the=
 use of AI tools appropriately.
     *   The Carleton University Senate met  in 2023<https://charlatan.ca/c=
arleton-senate-explores-generative-ai-in-academia/> to discuss the challeng=
es of generative artificial intelligence (AI) and considered recommendation=
s for its integration in an academic setting. One of the articles written i=
n the Charleton<https://charlatan.ca/carleton-senate-explores-generative-ai=
-in-academia/> noted that =93alongside other post-secondary institutions, C=
arleton University is exploring the use of AI technology in education, whic=
h previously posed academic integrity concerns.  The working group on the u=
se of AI in teaching and learning at Carleton University proposed their rep=
ort at a meeting on September 23, 2023. The group consisted of Carleton ins=
tructors, students and staff aiming to assess AI tools in education as new =
research becomes available.=94



Opportunities



With those two considerations in mind, I think this creates a fantastic opp=
ortunity for us to work with students and faculty in the TIM program to kic=
kstart a really cool conversation on campus about using AI tools appropriat=
ely to increase the efficiency in the way that they work, and by extension,=
 in the way that we tackle assignments, projects and problems in all facets=
 of their lives.   I=92ve been really impressed with how the TIM program ha=
s embraced the use of AI and its exploration of a number of tools that are =
currently available for a host of different tasks and challenges.  This wil=
l continue to be an asset for all of us in the future.  I know that other d=
epartments like Computer Science have also included the use of AI in their =
curriculum as it is changing the way their industries/academic spaces opera=
te.



I am going to ask Tony, Eduardo and a few other faculty members to help me =
facilitate a series of talks in the Innovation Hub that helps to open this =
conversation through an Innovation lens, and I propose that your session be=
 one of the first sessions to kickstart that series.  In addition to introd=
ucing some of the really good things about Perplexity and the ways that can=
 be used by students in the future, we can include some snippets from other=
 units/voices on campus to make sure that the conversation is always balanc=
ed.  This shifts the presentation from being one that focuses solely on Per=
plexity (I know that could be a challenge given your position as a campus r=
ep with Perplexity) and focuses mainly on innovative ways to leverage AI to=
ols while learning about that rapidly increasing number of options availabl=
e.



To make your own role easier, and dare I say more accepted on campus by oth=
er groups, we  need to  ensure that your team has also taken the time to co=
mplete the university=92s security and privacy assessment process<https://c=
arleton.ca/its/security/services/risk-assessment/>. I am sure that your col=
leagues will be able to help you provide the information the university nee=
ds to assess Perplexity.



I am happy to adjust the description of the session so that we can include =
a few other voices.



If you need to keep the session in its current form, then you should hold i=
t in a classroom instead of the Hub and then we will incorporate you into t=
he other series once it gets up and running.



Looking forward to continuing this conversation this week.



John Nelson

Director, Innovation Hub

